Currently just staked - the validator has control over those wallets. We could burn, but there are reasons not to:
1. if we just leave it staked, the staking rewards continue to accumulate to those wallets effectively reducing alpha from the pool automatically
2. if we burn, we lose the ability for the staked tokens to have any use in governance, e.g. if chutes becomes a DAO and we'd like to vote on proposals by stake weight, or if there's some future bittensor functionality which makes stake important for other reasons
There's no plan for the alpha at the moment - it's just staked and left staked forever. A burn would be "safer" in almost ever respect though; burn was not available when we first implemented the auto-staking.

@consτ [τ, τ]  To try to clarify, the rolling update logic is:
1. Calculate update rate to complete all updates within 45 minutes
2. If update time per instance > 5 minutes (i.e < 9 instances of that chute), default to 5 minutes b/t updating instances
     - So if you only had 2 instances of this chute it would update 1, wait 5 minutes, update the second instance.

## Miner upgrade guide

*before anything else, clone/git pull the latest `main` branch of https://github.com/rayonlabs/chutes-miner*

### Update gepetto
The changes here are quite extensive, so it's best to update the new version than try to modify your old version with the updates, otherwise you are at risk of missing some necessary logic.

Be sure to review and modify the `job_created` event according to your preferences
- Important to note that for jobs to be validated, you *must* have the same egress and ingress IP address - a mismatch will trigger the instance/job to automatically fail and could result in scoring punishments.
- Users will have direct access to the nodes on jobs (but by default nobody has access to create jobs, it's a permission/quota that must be manually granted), because jobs can be anything really including server rentals with SSH access (inside the pod though, not the host machine).
- Each job has a custom `compute_multiplier` which can be more (or less) than you would get for standard chutes, e.g. DeepSeek-V3-0324 has a multiplier of 5.4, but a job for an 8x h200 node might have a multiplier of 16, or 32, or whatever (still working on precise mechanism to adjust this to incentivize scheduling these)
- Be sure to have sufficient disk space on your GPU nodes for jobs - the new code automatically checks the disk space that is allocatable on each node before scheduling, but you may wish to adjust accordingly.

Once you are satisfied with your changes, push out your updated `gepetto-code` confimap:
```bash
kubectl create configmap gepetto-code --from-file=gepetto.py -o yaml --dry-run=client | kubectl apply -n chutes -f -
```
### Update network policies
From within the `charts` directory, run this to apply the updated network policy for normal chutes, and to create the new network policy for jobs.
```bash
helm template . -s templates/chutes-job-np.yaml -s templates/chutes-np.yaml | kubectl apply -n chutes -f -
```
### GPU node cache updates
Each chute will now have it's own dedicated cache directory on the GPU nodes, i.e. instead of shared `/var/snap/cache`, it will be `/var/snap/cache/{chute_id}`
The cleanup script will now properly ignore the chute that it's trying to deploy, but you need to update that script. From within the `charts` directory, run:
```bash
helm template . -s templates/cache-cleanup-cm.yaml | kubectl apply -n chutes -f -
```
You can try to "fix" the directory structure on your GPU nodes to avoid re-downloading each of the models, meaning you would need to get all of the `chute_id` values for each of the models you already have downloaded, then symlink or duplicate the corresponding `/var/snap/cache/hub/...` model to `/var/snap/cache/{chute_id}/hub/...` (honestly not sure if a simple symlink would work here).
The easy/lazy option is to just leave it alone and let the model be downloaded again from huggingface, but some nodes with connectivity/bandwidth issues could be problematic. The means by which you update your model cache are up to you.

### Update chutes-miner-cli
You can either use the pypi wheel, e.g. `pip3 install --upgrade chutes-miner-cli`, or you can install it from the repo, e.g. `pip3 install -e cli` (from within the chutes-miner git repo dir)
### Last step - update your API and gepetto deployments to use the new docker images
*Be sure to only do this once you've done all of the previous steps.*
First select the image/pull policy you wish to use:
1. Use the tagged version with today's date: `parachutes/miner:202507171600`
2. Use `latest` tag, i.e. `parachutes/miner:latest` but you'll need to make sure your `ImagePullPolicy` is set to `Always` so it pulls the newer versions.

Then, simply edit the deployment and change the `image:` and/or `ImagePullPolicy` values according to your choice. If you are comfortable with `vim`, you can run `kubectl edit deployment api -n chutes` and `kubectl edit deployment gepetto -n chutes`, otherwise you'll want to update and re-apply the helm charts (but only for the api and gepetto deployments, e.g. `helm template . -s templates/api-deployment.yaml -s templates/gepetto-deployment.yaml | kubectl apply -n chutes -f -`)

### Notes
You will not be able to run any new chutes, or jobs, without upgrading, and these are starting to be rolled out now, so please update soon. By the end of the week or early next week, all chutes will be upgraded to use the new library which is not backwards compatible.
Also you *must* update your cuda/nvidia drivers to 12.8+/570+. The "deadline" for this was a few weeks ago, but now it's becoming an actual blocker since we need the newer versions for blackwell support and other things.
